div.h1: Real Mode vs. Protected Mode: Address Translation

g.text: Why the Far Jump is Mandatory

p.strong: CPU State at Boot: 16-bit Real Mode
CPU State After Transition: 32-bit Protected Mode

div.p: Maximum addressable: 0x10FFEF (wraps to 0x0EFFEF due to 20-bit limit)
asm mov eax, cr0 or eax, 1 ; Set Protection Enable mov cr0, eax
CPU is NOW in protected mode!

ul.li: Loads new CS base/limit from GDT

div.p: asm mov ax, 0x10 ; Kernel data selector mov ds, ax mov es, ax mov ss, ax

Bit 7: Present (P) - 1 = segment in memory Bits 6-5: DPL - Privilege level (0-3) Bit 4: System (S) - 1 = code/data, 0 = system Bit 3: Executable (E) - 1 = code, 0 = data Bit 2: DC - Direction/Conforming Bit 1: RW - Readable/Writable Bit 0: Accessed (A) - Set by CPU when accessed
Base: 0x00000000 (all 0) Limit: 0xFFFFF (20-bit) Flags: G=1 (4KB granularity), D=1 (32-bit), L=0 (not 64-bit) Access: P=1, DPL=0, S=1, E=1, RW=1
After mov cr0, eax sets PE=1:

ol.li: CPU is technically in protected mode

BUT the prefetch queue still contains:
16-bit real-mode instructions
Old CS interpretation (shift, not selector)
Next instruction fetch uses corrupted state

Loads CS with selector 0x08:
GDT index 1 (kernel code segment)
RPL = 0 (kernel privilege)
TI = 0 (use GDT, not LDT)

Fetches new instruction from:
Linear address = GDT[1].base + offset
With 32-bit code segment attributes
